<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-492-655  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 492 655.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 14 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Brazil eases computer trade restrictions.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McCormick, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BrazilForeign CompetitionInternational tradeGovernment RegulationComputer industry.andO;Person:    Collor de Mello, Fernando (commercial policy).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>BRAZIL EASES COMPUTER TRADE RESTRICTIONS WASHINGTON, D.C., U.S.A., 1990 SEP14 (NB) -- Brazil's civilian government is bowing to increasing pressure toopen its markets to foreign computers and software.andP;  President FernandoCollor de Mello's government has announced that it will drop mostrestrictions on imports by the end of 1992 and will immediately reduce thelist of protected items.andM;President de Mello is attempting to wean the economy from the protectionismof 25 years of military rule and free up the world's sixth- to eighth-largestcomputer market to outside competition.andP;  Brazil has over 300 domesticcomputer companies with revenues exceeding $3.5 billion in 1989 but there areonly about 30 multinational companies, with revenues around $1.5 billion forthe same period.andM;The government had earlier removed the $1 billion limit on imported computerproducts, but this week's change promises much greater flexibility.andO;President de Mello's government has also pledged to loosen restrictions onjoint ventures and on the amount of &quot;local content&quot; required for importedsystems.andM;Digital Equipment already has a factory in Brazil, and Lotus Development hasa relatively large presence in the market.andM;Besides protectionism, Brazil, despite being one of the world's top tencomputer markets, presents a very troubled market picture to internationalvendors because of its historically high inflation rate.andP;  After President deMello froze bank accounts earlier this year software sales dropped to about20 percent of previous levels while hardware sales experienced a similarplunge.andM;The one major computer area where Brazil is anxious to buy from U.S.andP;  makersis in supercomputers, but here the U.S.andP;  government has delayed shipment ofCray computers because of fears that they would be used in a nuclear weaponsdevelopment program.andM;(John McCormick/19900914)</TEXT></DOC>